International Conference on Computational Science, ICCS 2013

Detecting DiÔ¨Äerentially Co-expressed Genes for Drug Target
Analysis
Xi Gaoa , Tomasz Arodza,‚àó
a Department of Computer Science, School of Engineering,
Virginia Commonwealth University, 401 W. Main St., Richmond, Virginia 23284-3019, USA

Abstract
Many novel therapeutics originally aimed at a speciÔ¨Åc protein have in fact complex target proÔ¨Åles and interact promiscuously
with many other proteins and pathways. Discovering new molecular targets and related pharmacodynamic eÔ¨Äectors for existing
drugs can help us understand mechanisms behind drug resistance, discover potential side eÔ¨Äects, and point to target for new
drugs. Often, the study of novel targets and receptors starts with building up diverse panel of drug sensitive and resistant cell
lines, which is then proÔ¨Åled using high-throughput method such as gene expression microarrays or proteomic arrays. Analysis
of proÔ¨Åling data requires statistical methods that move beyond univariate tests of diÔ¨Äerential expression between sensitive
and resistant cell lines. Here, we propose a new approach for analysing diÔ¨Äerential co-expression, which allows for detecting
changes of co-expression pattern in gene pairs, bringing spotlight on the diÔ¨Äerences in complex dynamic relationships and
regulation mechanisms between genes in sensitive and resistant phenotypes. In contrast to existing methods, the proposed
approach can deal with confounding factors such as tissue heterogeneity of the cell line panels that leads to presence of
clusters and outliers, and together with relatively small number of samples can result in many false discoveries. We applied
our method to study diÔ¨Äerences of gene co-expression patterns between cell lines sensitive and resistant to dasatinib, a novel
targeted anticancer drug, and we discovered a closely-linked network of diÔ¨Äerentially co-expressed genes related to molecular
eÔ¨Äects of the drug.
Keywords: Biological networks; DiÔ¨Äerential co-expression; Drug target analysis

1. Introduction
Improved understanding of cancer origins and progression has lead in recent years to the development of a
number of targeted therapeutics [1], designed to interact with a selected molecular target chosen based on its role
in the disease. One class of molecular targets that attracts focus of anti-cancer drug development eÔ¨Äorts is tyrosine
kinases [2], which have pivotal role in triggering trans-membrane signalling, cell-cycle control, cell growth, proliferation, apoptosis and other cellular signal transduction cascades [3]. Instead of non-selectively killing rapidly
dividing cells, targeted therapeutics function by inhibiting speciÔ¨Åc tyrosine kinases, thus deactivating downstream
signal transduction cascades [4]. For example, imatinib aims at inhibition of the ATP binding domain of Bcr-Abl
fusion protein, a permanently active tyrosine kinase caused by translocation between chromosome 9 and 22 that
leads to chronic myelogenous leukemia. However, despite early success in prolonging patient survival, resistance
‚àó Corresponding

