to tyrosine kinase inhibitors such as imatinib has become a common problem [5]. Second generation inhibitors,
such as dasatinib [6], are being developed to treat resistant tumours.
It is increasingly evident that even speciÔ¨Åcally targeted therapeutics have complex activity proÔ¨Åles and are
often promiscuous [7]. Imatinib was shown to bind to c-KIT, DDR1 and PDGFR [8]. Dasatinib, designed as a
dual Src/Abl inhibitor for imatinib-resistant cancer patients, turned out to have even broader target spectrum [8, 9].
These discoveries made possible repositioning of existing drugs towards other types of cancer [10]. Also, they
allow for tailoring the treatment to subgroups of patients with particular molecular patters [11]. Further, they bring
new knowledge on the possible side-eÔ¨Äects of the treatment and point to candidate targets for novel therapies.
Uncovering previously unknown target proteins and pathways for existing drugs typically involves analyses
of high-throughput in vitro assays, followed up by more detailed biochemical analyses [11]. The screening step
works by searching for molecular diÔ¨Äerences between cell lines sensitive to the drug and those resistant to it,
using modalities such as gene expression microarrays. At this step, the most common approach is to employ
statistical tests for diÔ¨Äerential expression of individual genes. However, a single-gene diÔ¨Äerence is not likely to
explain the complexity of drug eÔ¨Äects on studied disease [12]. Also, these methods only reveal eÔ¨Äects that are
strong enough to pass the threshold resulting from corrections for multiple hypothesis testing, and may also miss
diÔ¨Äerences that involve multiple genes, but don‚Äôt manifest themselves clearly in any gene individually. Another
approach is to create multivariate discriminative models that are able to predict which cell lines are sensitive and
which are resistant, based on patterns of gene expression. While these models may have good predictive power,
their interpretability is often poor.
2. DiÔ¨Äerential Co-Expression
DiÔ¨Äerential co-expression analysis is gaining attention in recent years as a tool for Ô¨Ånding phenotypic diÔ¨Äerences that are more complex than univariate diÔ¨Äerences, but has not been used yet in studying drug targets and
their downstream eÔ¨Äectors. The approach aims at detecting pairs of genes that show diÔ¨Äerences in gene regulation
and cellular signalling between two phenotypes. DiÔ¨Äerential co-expression brings a new perspective on diÔ¨Äerence
between phenotypes ‚Äì that a speciÔ¨Åc phenotype could result from diÔ¨Äerences in gene regulation that do not signiÔ¨Åcantly alter average expression levels of genes, but alter the pattern of behaviour of the genes in tandem. For
example, a pair of genes may be tightly correlated in drug sensitive cells, where one of the genes regulates the
other, but uncorrelated in resistant cells, where the regulation is lost due to mutation. This idea has been proven
true in a lot of biological conditions such as obesity [13], aging [14] and cancer [15].
Existing diÔ¨Äerential co-expression detection methods usually measure some gene pair relationship score separately in each phenotype condition, then compare the diÔ¨Äerence of these scores. The score most often used is the
Pearson correlation coeÔ¨Écient, applied in conjunction with Fisher‚Äôs Z transformation [16, 17] that yields a probability distribution of the diÔ¨Äerences in correlation. However, Pearson correlation coeÔ¨Écient is highly aÔ¨Äected
by outlying samples. EÔ¨Äorts to make correlation more resilient to outliers were undertaken by using biweight
midcorrelation [18]. Rank-based and entropy-based measurements [19], as well as F-statistic [20] are also used.
In terms of the number of gene as a unit in the diÔ¨Äerential co-expression network, some methods aim at gene pairs
while others aim at gene modules [21, 22, 23].
Here, we report an approach for diÔ¨Äerential co-expression analysis of molecular determinants of cell lines
response to drugs. We focus on a recently introduced tyrosine kinase inhibitor dasatinib, and its response proÔ¨Åle
in the NCI-60 panel of cell lines, the most widely studied cell line used for anti-cancer drug development. We
present an integrated method for dealing with problems common in cell line panels used for drug screens, such as
diversity of cell types, presence of outliers, and existence of tissue clusters. These problems make existing methods
for diÔ¨Äerential co-expression unsuitable for studying such complex datasets. To illustrate this, we applied ROSDET [18], a recently published method for diÔ¨Äerential co-expression designed to be more resilient to outliers,
range bias and small sample size, to a dataset of cell lines from the NCI-60 panel, preprocessed as described in
Section 3 and 4.1. We present the 10 most highly ranked diÔ¨Äerential co-expression gene pairs detected by ROSDET in Fig. 1. With the exception of the PSMG1 - OSBPL7 pair (Fig. 1, top row, second plot from left), no clear
evidence for diÔ¨Äerential co-expression can be observed in the top ranked pairs. In all cases, the two classes overlap,
and outliers pose a problem, as can be seen in the third (TXNDC11-CCDC101) and fourth (PFAS-AGBL4) best
ranked pairs. These results show the need for new, improved methods for detecting diÔ¨Äerential co-expression.

