and ni is the number of samples in group i. As z approximately follows normal distribution, we could get the
probability of null hypothesis H0 : r1 = r2 and reject it at certain level of signiÔ¨Åcance. Here, we keep gene pairs
that are statistically signiÔ¨Åcant at 0.05 after Bonferroni correction as the Ô¨Ånal result of our method.
Statistically speaking, highly correlation coeÔ¨Écients with small diÔ¨Äerence, say r1 = 0.99 and r2 = 0.9 are
equally diÔ¨Äerent as high and low correlation coeÔ¨Écient, say r1 = 0.9 and r2 = 0.3. However, biologically speaking,
we are much more interested in detecting the second case which indicates impaired regulation in one class. So we
correct any correlation coeÔ¨Écient greater than 0.95 or less than -0.95 to 0.95 and -0.95, respectively, to avoid its
eÔ¨Äect on result.

